<dl id="n10015f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10015f">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10015f"> 15(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Halldor Snorasson /Halldoorway <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n10015f"><li>FW 435.35 </li><li><a href="../../flex/qA/lexqA.htm#n10015f">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/qA/l39qA.htm#n10015f">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n10015f">MS BL 47482b-28</ms> </li><li>JJA 57:057 <a name="qA2d" href="../../ff/fdra/qda.htm#qA2d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/q/qA2d.htm#n10015f">Draft: III&sect;2A.2</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The passages quoted from Nj&aacute;la Saga <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> seem to show that the art of story-telling was already developed at the beginning of the eleventh century.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Far more important is the passage from Haralds Saga Hardrada, for there the story-teller was not an eyewitness, but had obtained the story, or the material for it, from <mark>Halld&oacute;r Snorrason</mark>, an Icelandic follower of King Harald. <small> A. WALSH, <a name="AWSR" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#AWSR"><cite title="source">Scandinavian Relations with Ireland During the Viking Period</cite></a> (1922) 63-4</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See also <a name="n11063g" href="n11all.htm#n11063g">N11 (VI.B.5):063(g)</a>. </mm> </dd></dl>
